Parameters v. statistics

  • The population mean is a parameter.

    • parameters are numbers that describe (a model of) a population

  • The sample mean is a statistic

    • statistics are numbers that are computed from a sample

The goal of point estimation is to find a statistic that is a “good” estimate of a parameter

Example

The length of human pregnancies has a mean of 266 days and a standard deviation of 16 days. A random sample of 9 pregnant women was observed to have a mean pregnancy length of 270 days, with a standard deviation of 14 days. Identify the parameters and accompanying statistics in this situation.

Parameters

  • mean of 266 days, standard deviation of 16 days

Statistics

  • sample mean of 270 days, sample standard deviation of 14 days

Example

If students picked numbers completely at random from the numbers 1 to 20, the proportion of times that the number 7 would be picked is .05. When 15 students picked a number “at random” from 1 to 20, 3 of them picked the number 7. Identify the parameter and accompanying statistic in this situation.

Parameter

  • proportion is 0.05 (according to the random selection model)

Statistic

  • sample proportion is 3/15

Stat 202 focuses on

Population Parameters

Continous

  • Population mean: \( \mu \)
  • Population standard deviation: \( \sigma \)

Categorical

  • Population proportion: \( p \)

Sample Statistics

Continuous

  • Sample mean: \( \bar{x} \)
  • Sample standard deviation: \( s \)

Categorical

  • Sample proportion: \( \hat{p} \)

Make a histogram

The sample proportion \( \hat{p} \)

  • is different for different samples
  • has a sampling distribution

The sampling distribution of a sample proportion is often approximately normal.

Approximately normal (usually)

  • \( p \) is the population proportion
    • 60% of part-time college students are female
  • \( n \) the sample size
    • take a random sample of 20 part-time students

Approximately normal (when?)

If

\[ np \ge 10 \]

and

\[ n(1-p) \ge 10 \]

then \( \hat{p} \) is approximately normal.

Example:
\( 20 \times .6 = 12 \), but \( 20 \times (.4) = 8 \)

Not quite normal!

Approximately normal (when?)

Proportion female of 20 students

\[ p = .6 \quad n = 20 \]

Proportion female of 40 students

\[ p = .6 \quad n = 40 \]

Approximately normal (which?)

If \[ \begin{aligned} np & \ge 10 & & \text{and} & n(1-p) \ge 10 \end{aligned} \]

then \( \hat{p} \) is approximately normal:

\[ \hat{p} \sim N\left( p, \frac{p(1-p)}{n} \right) \]

Where the mean and standard deviation of \( \hat{p} \) are:

\[ \begin{aligned} E[\hat{p}] & = p & & & \text{sd}[\hat{p}] & = \sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}} \end{aligned} \]

As \( n \) increases, \( \hat{p} \) is likely to be closer to the population proportion \( \hat{p} \).

Approximately normal (which?)

Proportion female of 100 students

\[ p = .6 \quad n = 100 \]

Proportion female of 200 students

\[ p = .6 \quad n = 200 \]

An example problem

In 1998 (the most recent data available!) 70% of Nortwestern students were white (non-hispanic), 20% were asian, and 10% were of other ethnicities.

Consider a random sample of 50 Northwestern students. Are the

  • sample proportion of white students,
  • sample proportion of asian studetns, and/or
  • sample proportion of “other” students

approximately normally distributed?

An example problem (white)

70% of Nortwestern students were white (non-hispanic), 20% were asian, and 10% were of other ethnicities. Consider random sample of 50 Northwestern students. Is the sample proportion of white students approximately normally distributed?

What are \( p \) and \( n \)?

\( p = .80 \) and \( n= 50 \)

Approximately normal?

\( np = 50 \times .70 = 40 \) and \( n(1-p) = 50 \times .30 = 15 \) both \( \ge 10 \), therefore yes

An example problem (other)

70% of Nortwestern students were white (non-hispanic), 20% were asian, and 10% were of other ethnicities. Consider random sample of 50 Northwestern students. Is the sample proportion of “other” students approximately normally distributed?

What are \( p \) and \( n \)?

\( p = .10 \) and \( n= 50 \)

Approximately normal?

\( np = 50 \times .10 = 5 \) and \( n(1-p) = 50 \times .90 = 45 \) not both \( \ge 10 \), therefore no

An example problem (white)

In 1998 (the most recent data available!) 70% of Nortwestern students were white (non-hispanic), 20% were asian, and 10% were of other ethnicities.

There is a 95% chance that the sample proportion of white students will fall betwen what two values?

  • As shown, the sample proportion of white students is approximately normal.

  • What are the mean and standard deviation of this approximate normal distribution?

An example problem (white)

70% of Nortwestern students were white (non-hispanic), 20% were asian, and 10% were of other ethnicities. There is a 95% chance that the sample proportion of white students will fall betwen what two values?

\( p \), \( n \), and approx normal?: \( p = .70 \), \( n= 50 \), and yes.

Mean of \( \hat{p} \)?

  • \( E[ \hat{p} ] = p = .70 \)

SD of \( \hat{p} \)?

  • \( \text{sd}[\hat{p}] = \sqrt{\frac{p(1-p)}{n}} = \sqrt{\frac{.7(1-.7)}{50}} = 0.0648 \)

An example problem (white)

70% of Nortwestern students were white (non-hispanic), 20% were asian, and 10% were of other ethnicities. There is a 95% chance that the sample proportion of white students will fall betwen what two values?

\( p \), \( n \), and approx. normal?: \( p = .70 \), \( n= 50 \), and yes.

\( \hat{p} \) is approx. normal with mean of .8 and standard deviation of 0.057.

68/95/99.7 rule: \[ \begin{aligned} .7 - 2 \times 0.0648 & = .57 & & \text{and} & .7 + 2 \times 0.0648 & = .83 \end{aligned} \]
